    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-03-31T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-03-31T03:00:00-05:00" n="891"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d891">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.628/148: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-03-31T17:00:00+09:00"
                            >March 31, 1936—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 31—6:49 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>82. Department’s 37, March 28, 3 p.m. The Foreign Office informs the Embassy
                    orally that no licenses to take salmon in waters adjacent to Alaska have been
                    issued to Japanese vessels; that such action is not contemplated at present and
                    that the Japanese authorities have no knowledge of any Japanese fishing craft in
                    Bering Sea at this time. The Embassy is further informed that there would be no
                    objection to giving this assurance to interested persons.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
